@flexiarg math-informal/structural-inclusion
@title Structural Inclusion / Monotonicity
@sigils [⊆/包]
@keywords inclusion, containment, monotonicity, embedding, sub-structure, ordering
@audience mathematicians, algebraists, geometers
@tone analytic
@factor Wisdom (paññā)
@family math-strategy/structural-relation-result
@references [math-informal/transport-across-isomorphism math-informal/pass-to-a-subsequence math-informal/find-the-right-abstraction]

! conclusion:
  Show that one structure contains, embeds into, or is dominated by another —
  with directional preservation of the relevant invariants. Strictly weaker
  than equivalence; strictly stronger than mere correlation.

  + context: Two structures X and Y are in view, and the paper's contribution
    is to establish that X is contained in Y (in some structural sense), or
    that an invariant on X is dominated by the analogous invariant on Y, or
    that X embeds as a sub-object of Y.

  + IF:
      You can construct an order-preserving / structure-preserving map
      X → Y, or argue that the unit ball / minimal class / norm of X is
      contained in that of Y, with directional rather than symmetric
      content.

  + HOWEVER:
      Structural inclusion differs from `transport-across-isomorphism`: that
      pattern is symmetric (X ≅ Y); this pattern is directional (X ⊆ Y but
      not necessarily Y ⊆ X). Inclusion alone is weaker but often more
      useful in practice — many monotonicity results carry strict inclusion
      that no equivalence can replicate. Use this leaf when the relation is
      genuinely one-way.

  + THEN:
      1. Identify the inclusion / embedding / domination map and verify it
         preserves the structural feature of interest.
      2. Verify that the inclusion is strict (or note explicitly when it is
         tight / non-strict).
      3. Identify the consequence: what holds for X because it holds for Y,
         or what fails to hold because the reverse inclusion does not.

  + BECAUSE:
      Inclusion / monotonicity statements are the workhorses of comparison:
      they let one transfer results from a well-understood object to a less-
      understood one, or rule out behaviour by appeal to a containing
      structure. Cobordism, norm-domination, lattice-embedding, and
      sub-representation arguments all live here.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
      next[Construct the structural map and verify directional preservation.]
      next[Determine whether the inclusion is strict or tight.]
      next[Identify the property of X that this inclusion gives access to.]
